1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:We propose a novel method of analysing data gathered from TREC or similar information retrieval evaluation experiments .
1-2:We define two normalized versions of average precision, that we use to construct a weighted bipartite graph of TREC systems and topics .
1-3:We analyze the meaning of well known and somewhat generalized indicators from social network analysis on the Systems Topics graph .
1-4:We apply this method to an analysis of TREC 8 data; among the results, we find that authority measures systems performance, that hubness of topics reveals that some topics are better than others at distinguishing more or less effective systems, that with current measures a system that wants to be effective in TREC needs to be effective on easy topics, and that by using different effectiveness measures this is no longer the case .
1-5:H.3.3 [Information Storage and Retrieval]: Information .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:Evaluation is a primary concern in the Information Retrieval field .
2-2:TREC (Text REtrieval Conference) [12, 15] is an annual benchmarking exercise that has become a de facto standard in IR evaluation: before the actual conference, TREC provides to participants a collection of documents and a set of topics (representations of information needs) .
2-3:Participants use their systems to retrieve, and submit to TREC, a list of documents for each topic .
2-4:After the lists have been submitted and pooled, the TREC organizers employ human assessors to provide relevance judgements on the pooled set .
2-5:This defines a set of relevant documents for each topic .
2-6:System effectiveness is then measured by well established metrics (Mean Average Precision being the most used) .
2-7:Other conferences such as NTCIR, INEX, CLEF provide comparable data .
2-8:Network analysis is a discipline that studies features and properties of (usually large) networks, or graphs .
2-9:Of particular importance is Social Network Analysis [16], that studies networks made up by links among humans (friendship, acquaintance, co authorship, bibliographic citation, etc.) .
2-10:Network analysis and IR fruitfully meet in Web Search Engine implementation, as is already described in textbooks [3,6] .
2-11:Current search engines use link analysis techniques to help rank the retrieved documents .
2-12:Some indicators (and the corresponding algorithms that compute them) have been found useful in this respect, and are nowadays well known: Inlinks (the number of links to a Web page), PageRank [7], and HITS (Hyperlink Induced Topic Search) [5] .
2-13:Several extensions to these algorithms have been and are being proposed .
2-14:These indicators and algorithms might be quite general in nature, and can be used for applications which are very different from search result ranking .
2-15:One example is using HITS for stemming, as described by Agosti et al .
2-16:[1] .
2-17:In this paper, we propose and demonstrate a method for constructing a network, specifically a weighted complete bidirectional directed bipartite graph, on a set of TREC topics and participating systems .
2-18:Links represent effectiveness measurements on system topic pairs .
2-19:We then apply analysis methods originally developed for search applications to the resulting network .
2-20:This reveals phenomena previously hidden in TREC data .
2-21:In passing, we also provide a small generalization to Kleinberg"s HITS algorithm, as well as to Inlinks and PageRank .
2-22:The paper is organized as follows: Sect .
2-23:2 gives some motivations for the work .
2-24:Sect .
2-25:3 presents the basic ideas of normalizing average precision and of constructing a systemstopics graph, whose properties are analyzed in Sect .
2-26:4; Sect .
2-27:5 presents some experiments on TREC 8 data; Sect .
2-28:6 discusses some issues and Sect .
2-29:7 closes the paper. .
